<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Look for Cabernets with 13.5-15% Alcohol</strong> - The best Cabernet Sauvignon balances power with elegance. Wines over 15% often mask the grape's signature cassis and cedar notes with alcohol heat, while those under 13.5% may lack the concentration that makes great Cabernet age-worthy. Premier producers like Screaming Eagle and Château Margaux consistently hit this sweet spot.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Serve at Precisely 60-65°F for Optimal Expression</strong> - Cabernet Sauvignon's complex tannin structure requires this specific temperature range. Too cold (below 60°F) and the tannins become harsh and the fruit muted; too warm (above 65°F) and the alcohol dominates, masking the wine's terroir-driven minerality and structured backbone that defines premium bottlings.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Decant Young Cabernets for 2-3 Hours, Aged for 30-60 Minutes</strong> - Cabernet Sauvignon under 8 years needs extended aeration to soften its naturally high tannins and allow secondary flavors like tobacco and leather to emerge. Wines over 15 years are more fragile—brief decanting preserves their evolved tertiary aromas of forest floor and graphite while removing any sediment.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Use Bordeaux-Style Glasses with 22-24 oz Capacity</strong> - Cabernet Sauvignon's aromatic compounds—particularly pyrazines that create its signature bell pepper and cedar notes—need substantial bowl space to concentrate properly. The narrower rim of Bordeaux glasses focuses these complex aromas while the large bowl allows optimal oxidation of the wine's phenolic compounds.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Age Premium Cabernets 8-12 Years for Peak Complexity</strong> - The best Cabernet Sauvignon develops its most compelling character when primary fruit evolves into secondary and tertiary flavors. Napa Valley cult wines and Bordeaux First Growths typically hit their stride after a decade, when tannins have polymerized and the wine shows classic cedar, cigar box, and graphite minerality alongside mature fruit.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Drink Bordeaux Left Bank Earlier Than Napa Valley</strong> - Due to blending with Merlot and Cabernet Franc, Bordeaux Left Bank Cabernets (Pauillac, Saint-Julien, Saint-Estèphe) often become approachable at 10-15 years. Pure Napa Valley Cabernet Sauvignon, with higher alcohol and concentration, benefits from 12-20 years of aging to reach its full potential and showcase its distinctive Rutherford dust or Howell Mountain power.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Identify Premium Cabernet by Its "Grip" and Length</strong> - The finest Cabernet Sauvignon exhibits a distinctive tannic "grip" that coats the entire palate without being harsh, followed by a finish that lasts 30-45 seconds with evolving flavors. This structure comes from perfectly ripe grapes and careful extraction—hallmarks of producers like Harlan Estate, Château Latour, and Caymus Special Selection.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Match Food Intensity to Cabernet's Power Level</strong> - Best Cabernet Sauvignon's high tannins and full body require substantial proteins and fats. Bordeaux-style blends pair beautifully with herb-crusted lamb, while bold Napa Cabernets shine with ribeye or aged cheeses. The wine's natural acidity and tannins cleanse the palate between bites, making each sip as impactful as the first.</li>
</ol>



