<p>Understanding Cabernet Sauvignon price tiers helps you maximize your investment. In the <strong>$15-25 range</strong>, seek Washington State producers like Charles Smith or Australian regions like Coonawarra—these offer structured wines with good fruit concentration. The <strong>$25-50 tier</strong> opens doors to exceptional value from Paso Robles (Justin, Daou) and Argentina's high-altitude Mendoza vineyards, where you'll find wines with genuine complexity and aging potential.</p>

<p>The <strong>$50-100 category</strong> delivers serious Napa Valley expressions from established producers like Stag's Leap Wine Cellars or Caymus, alongside premium Bordeaux from lesser-known châteaux in Saint-Estèphe or Pessac-Léognan. Above <strong>$100</strong>, you're investing in cult Napa Cabernets, First Growth Bordeaux, or limited-production single-vineyard bottlings that offer profound complexity and decades of aging potential.</p>

