<li><strong>Position</strong>: Store bottles horizontally to keep corks moist</li>
<li><strong>Light</strong>: Complete darkness to prevent UV damage</li>
<li><strong>Vibration</strong>: Minimize movement to avoid sediment disturbance</li>
</ul>

<h3>Peak Drinking Windows</h3>
<p class="bg-wine-50 p-4 rounded-lg">Bordeaux-style blends often require 8-10 years to integrate, while New World Cabernets may show beautifully at 5-7 years. Monitor cork condition and wine level—proper aging shows gradual color evolution and increasing complexity, while spoilage presents as vinegar aromas, brown coloration, or significant ullage (air space) in the bottle.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What makes a Cabernet Sauvignon one of the "best" compared to other bottles?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The best Cabernet Sauvignons demonstrate exceptional balance between tannin structure, acidity, and fruit concentration, with clear expression of their terroir. They exhibit complexity through layers of dark fruit, earth, and oak integration, plus the ability to age gracefully for 10-20+ years. Premium examples from regions like Napa Valley, Bordeaux Left Bank, or Coonawarra show distinctive characteristics that reflect their specific vineyard sites and winemaking philosophy.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I decant the best Cabernet Sauvignon bottles before serving?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, most premium Cabernet Sauvignons benefit significantly from decanting, especially bottles under 10 years old or those with substantial tannin structure. Decanting for 1-2 hours allows the wine to open up, softening harsh tannins and revealing hidden aromatics like cedar, tobacco, and dark chocolate. Very old bottles (15+ years) may only need 30 minutes to avoid over-aeration, while young, powerful Cabs from Napa or Barossa can handle 3+ hours of decanting.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between Napa Valley and Bordeaux Cabernet Sauvignon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Napa Valley Cabernet Sauvignons typically showcase riper, more opulent fruit with higher alcohol (14-15.5%), emphasizing blackberry and cassis with vanilla oak integration. Bordeaux Left Bank Cabernets (often blended with Merlot and Cabernet Franc) display more restrained fruit, higher acidity, graphite minerality, and earthy undertones with alcohol around 12.5-14%. Napa styles are generally more approachable young, while Bordeaux requires longer aging to reach peak drinking condition.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are expensive Cabernet Sauvignons always better than affordable ones?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Not necessarily – while price often correlates with quality factors like vineyard site, yields, and winemaking techniques, exceptional value exists in regions like Washington State, Chile's Maipo Valley, and Australia's Coonawarra. Many $25-40 bottles from producers like Chateau Ste. Michelle, Santa Rita, or Wolf Blass can rival $100+ wines in blind tastings. The key is understanding what drives price: prestigious appellations, low production, cult status, and marketing often inflate costs beyond actual quality differences.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long should I cellar the best Cabernet Sauvignon before drinking?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Premium Cabernet Sauvignons typically need 5-8 years minimum to integrate tannins and develop secondary characteristics like leather, cedar, and forest floor. Top-tier bottles from Napa's Oakville/Rutherford or Bordeaux's Pauillac can improve for 15-25 years, reaching peak complexity around years 10-15. However, modern winemaking produces more approachable styles – many excellent Cabs are designed to drink well upon release while still having aging potential.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Cabernet Sauvignon a good choice for wine beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Cabernet Sauvignon can be challenging for beginners due to its bold tannins and full body, but it's an excellent learning wine for developing palate sophistication. Start with fruit-forward examples from warmer climates like California Central Coast or Australian Barossa Valley, which offer more approachable sweetness and softer tannins. Avoid highly tannic, austere styles from Bordeaux or cooler climates until your palate develops tolerance for structural elements.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the biggest mistakes people make when buying premium Cabernet Sauvignon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is buying based solely on critic scores or brand reputation without considering drinking timeline and food pairing intentions. Many people purchase young, tannic Cabernets expecting immediate gratification, leading to disappointment with harsh, closed wines. Another error is overlooking outstanding value regions like Washington State or Margaret River in favor of prestigious but overpriced Napa cult wines that may not offer proportional quality improvements.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wines are similar to Cabernet Sauvignon if I want alternatives?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Malbec from Argentina offers similar dark fruit intensity with softer tannins and plush texture, making it more immediately approachable. Bordeaux-style blends provide complexity while moderating Cabernet's intensity through Merlot and Cabernet Franc additions. For those seeking structure with different flavor profiles, try Nebbiolo from Barolo (more floral, tar-like) or Tempranillo from Ribera del Duero (leathery, earthy with bright acidity).</p>
